Introduction

Although there was a lot of data available, I lost some time finding data with which I could establish relationships and perform analysis. However, I eventually decided to examine the data on Online Shopping,Consumer Confidence Index and Total Number of Closed Businesses and to conduct regressions on these topics. These were subjects of interest to me. While examining the changes in these data, I had the opportunity to discover new things.

First of all, lets install packages and read our data.

Model 1

Lets start by examining the Online Shopping topic. We can begin our analysis by looking at our data.

ggplot(data ,aes(x=Tarih,y=int_alisverisi, group=1)) + geom_line()

When analyzing the topic of online shopping, considering Google searches related to holidays and discounts can be very helpful for our analysis. Lets explore the relationship between these searches and our topic.

ggplot(data ,aes(x=bayram_search,y=int_alisverisi)) + geom_point() +geom_smooth(method='lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Now, lets create a plot to see the correlation by month. Note:Running this code chunk once is enough for the whole progress.

data[,trnd:=1:.N]
data[,mon:=as.character(month(Tarih,label=T))]
data[,yl:=as.character(year(Tarih))]
ggplot(data,aes(x=bayram_search,y=int_alisverisi)) +
        geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm,linewidth=3) + facet_wrap(~mon)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Lets inspect if our online shopping data is correlated with itself.

acf(data$int_alisverisi)

With taking trend into consideration, lets start to build our model. We observed the trend when we first inspected the visualization of the data.

lm_base=lm(int_alisverisi~trnd,data)
summary(lm_base)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals
## Q* = 563.38, df = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
## Model df: 0.   Total lags used: 10
tmp=copy(data)
tmp[,actual:=int_alisverisi]
tmp[,predicted_trend:=predict(lm_base,tmp)]
tmp[,residual_trend:=actual-predicted_trend]
#head(tmp)
ggplot(tmp ,aes(x=Tarih)) +
        geom_line(aes(y=actual,color='real')) + 
        geom_line(aes(y=predicted_trend,color='predicted'))

Now, its time to look at the relationship between holiday searches and our data. When using the holiday search data to explain our data, we can actually see that this is a very accurate method. This is because our R-squared value is high, which indicates that our model is on the right track. But keep in mind there is still a lot to improve.

## Model 2

In this model, we will be looking at the Consumer Confidence Index, which is a measure of consumers optimism or pessimism about the economys prospects, and its impact on their spending and saving behavior.

Lets check the data visualization first.

ggplot(data ,aes(x=Tarih,y=tketici_gven_endeksi, group=1)) + geom_line()

The commercial interest rate and real confidence index data seem like useful information to explain our data. Therefore, lets add them to our model and examine their effects.

ggplot(data ,aes(x=ticari_faiz,y=tketici_gven_endeksi)) + geom_point() +geom_smooth(method='lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Now we could check the year effect to see the relation. As observed in the bottom this improves our model, but we still have a very week model with a very low r-squared value. The exponential growth of the number of closed businesses could be interpreted with the use of logarithm function. This would take out the exp. effect and we would have a smoother graph.
